I. Creational Patterns (5 patterns)
Creational Design Patterns deal with how objects are created in an application.
Instead of creating objects directly using new, these patterns provide flexible and controlled ways to instantiate objects.

They are needed & help to:
    Control object creation
    Reduce tight coupling
    Improve code flexibility
    Hide creation logic from the client

1) Singleton: it ensures that a class has only one instance and provide a global access point to it.
Ex: Loggers, Database Connection Pool, Config Manager, Cache, Thread Pool.. etc.
2) Factory Method: - "Tell me what you want, I'll create it for you — you don't need to know how it's made."
Core idea: Move object creation logic out of client code into a dedicated factory.

3) Abstract Factory: Move object creation logic out of client code into a dedicated factory.
4) Builder: Construct a complex object step-by-step, and only build it when you're ready.
5) Prototype:Instead of creating a new object from scratch, clone an existing one and tweak only what's different.
6) Object Pool: Object Pool Design Pattern
